[49m[38;5;10m+     1[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Recipe 11.9: Care Coordination Assistant
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     2[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     3[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Complexity:** Complex · **Phase:** Regulated · **Estimated Cost:** ~$4-18 per active member per month (depends on engagement frequency, channel mix, model choice, RAG depth, multi-system integration depth, referral-tracking complexity, and human care-management overhead)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     4[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     5[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     6[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     7[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Problem
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     8[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     9[0m:[38;5;10m[49m David is 67. Three weeks ago he was sitting in his cardiologist's office, listening to a sentence he had been half-expecting and half-dreading for several years, which is that the moderate aortic stenosis the cardiologist had been watching since 2019 had progressed to severe and that David was now a candidate for a transcatheter aortic valve replacement procedure. The cardiologist used the abbreviation TAVR, drew a quick diagram of an aortic valve and a catheter, and explained that David would need to see a structural heart specialist at the academic medical center forty-five minutes away, that he would also need a CT angiogram of his chest and a workup with a cardiothoracic surgeon for a comparison evaluation, that there would be pulmonary function tests and a carotid ultrasound and a dental clearance and a few other items, that the structural heart team would coordinate the workup once David was referred, and that the goal was to have everything ready for a multidisciplinary heart team review in six to eight weeks. The cardiologist was reassuring. The cardiologist was thorough. The cardiologist had ten more patients on the schedule that day. David left the office holding a stack of papers, a referral printout, an instruction sheet, and a feeling that what had just been described as "we'll get this organized" was, from the patient side, going to involve significantly more work than the word "organized" suggested.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    10[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    11[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Three weeks later, David is sitting at his kitchen table with the papers spread out in front of him, the calendar open on his phone, and a yellow legal pad on which he has been trying to draw a chart of who is supposed to call whom and when. The structural heart center called him to confirm a consultation appointment, and then a different person at the same number called him about a pre-procedure CT scan. The cardiothoracic surgeon's office called him about a separate consultation, and somebody from that office told him he would need pulmonary function tests beforehand, but they did not schedule the pulmonary function tests, and he is not sure if his cardiologist's office is supposed to do that or if the surgeon's office is, and when he called the surgeon's office back to ask, the person who answered did not know either. His own cardiologist's office sent him a message in the patient portal asking him to schedule the carotid ultrasound at the imaging center across town, but the imaging center says they need an order from the cardiologist's office, and the order has not arrived, and David has called twice, but he is on hold. The dental clearance is supposed to be done by his dentist, and his dentist's office said sure, they could do that, but they would need a specific form from the cardiologist's office, and the cardiologist's office said the dentist could just write a letter, and the dentist said they wanted the form, and David is now in the middle of a small bureaucratic loop he did not ask for. His primary care physician's office called yesterday to schedule his annual physical, and David said he would do it after the procedure, and the scheduler said okay, but then this morning his primary care physician's office sent him a message asking when he would like to schedule his diabetes follow-up, which he had assumed was the same as his annual physical but is apparently a separate visit. His insurance company called to tell him that one of the imaging studies he was being asked to do was going to require a prior authorization, and they could not tell him whether the cardiologist's office had submitted it yet. He is not sure who his "care team" is, exactly. The cardiologist said something about the structural heart center's coordinator, but David cannot remember her name, and the phone number is on a piece of paper in his car. The list on the legal pad has fifteen items, four of which have been scheduled, two of which are blocked on something or somebody he cannot identify, and the rest of which are in some state he does not know how to characterize.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    12[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    13[0m:[38;5;10m[49m David is not unusual. David is, in healthcare-system terms, doing reasonably well. He has insurance, he has a stable home life, he has a wife who helps him with the phone calls, he has a smartphone he can use, and he has the time and energy to keep a yellow legal pad with a list on it. He is also drowning in the operational reality of what it takes for a patient to navigate a complex multi-specialty care journey in the U.S. healthcare system in 2026, and the small bureaucratic loops he is in are filling up the calendar and producing, in him, the slow accumulation of frustration and anxiety that is one of the most reliably-occurring patient experiences in this country. The procedure has not yet happened. The handoffs have barely begun.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    14[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    15[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The thing David needs, although nobody has used this exact phrase with him, is care coordination. Not the version of care coordination that exists as a category on the institutional org chart and is staffed by a small number of nurse care coordinators reserved for the highest-risk transitions. Care coordination as a daily lived experience for patients with complex care journeys, which is to say: the work of keeping track of who has done what, who is supposed to do what next, what is blocked on what, what is overdue, what has been scheduled, what has been completed, what the results were, and how the next step depends on the previous step. This work, when it is done at all in U.S. healthcare, is mostly done by patients, by patients' family members, by occasional ad-hoc nurse coordinators in specific high-acuity programs (transplant, oncology, structural heart, specific surgical pathways), and by medical assistants in primary-care offices doing the parts they can do for the patients they have time for. Most of the time, for most of the patients, most of this work is the patient's job, and most patients are not equipped to do it well, and the system absorbs the resulting failures (missed appointments, delayed care, redundant testing, lost referrals, dropped follow-up, increased complications, increased cost, increased mortality) as a baseline operational reality.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    16[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    17[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The economics make the problem worse. Healthcare in the U.S. is structured into specialty silos that bill independently, document independently, communicate inconsistently, and have no shared workflow infrastructure for coordinating care across silo boundaries. <!-- TODO: verify; the fragmented nature of U.S. healthcare delivery and its association with care-coordination failures is documented in extensive literature including reports from the Institute of Medicine, the Agency for Healthcare Research and Quality, and the National Academy of Medicine; specific findings vary --> Each specialty has its own scheduling system, its own referral process, its own portal, its own intake forms, its own pre-visit instructions, and its own post-visit follow-up cadence. The patient, who is the only entity with a complete view of their own care journey, is also the entity with the least training in healthcare workflow and the least operational capacity to manage it. The mismatch between the patient's role and the patient's preparation for the role is, by some measures, one of the largest sources of avoidable cost and avoidable suffering in the system.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    18[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    19[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The previous generations of digital tools tried to address this in ways that did not quite work. Patient portals gave patients a window into their own data, which was an improvement over having no window, but did not give them a way to coordinate the work across multiple portals at multiple institutions. Care plans were written down on paper and given to patients at discharge, where they functioned as a record of what was decided and not as a tool for tracking what happened next. Care-management programs, where they exist, reach a small fraction of patients, mostly the ones identified as high-risk by clinical or actuarial criteria. The broad middle of patients, who have multi-step care journeys but do not qualify for nurse care management, navigate the journey themselves with whatever supports their family and personal resources allow.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    20[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    21[0m:[38;5;10m[49m What changed, around 2023, is that conversational AI got good enough to act as a care-coordination layer that could see across the silos in ways the patient could not. A bot that has access to the patient's referrals, scheduled appointments, completed appointments, pending orders, prior-authorization status, test results, care-plan milestones, and care-team contacts can, in conversation with the patient, do the work the patient has been doing on the legal pad: keep track of what has happened, what is supposed to happen next, what is blocked on what, what is overdue, and who needs to do something about it. The bot can answer the patient's question "what am I supposed to do this week?" with a useful answer. The bot can answer the question "is the prior authorization for my CT done yet?" by checking and reporting back. The bot can recognize, when the patient says "I haven't heard back from the surgeon's office," that the referral has been sitting unscheduled for two weeks and surface that to a human care navigator. The bot is not the nurse coordinator. The bot is, in the right product design, the operational layer that lets the nurse coordinator workflow scale to the broad middle of complex-care-journey patients that nurse coordination cannot reach.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    22[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    23[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This recipe is about that bot. The care coordination assistant is the recipe in this chapter where the architectural patterns from the previous chapter 11 recipes converge into the most cross-institutional, cross-system, longest-context, and most operationally-integrated of the patient-facing bots: it has to read across the EHR, the referral management system, the scheduling system, the imaging system, the lab system, the pharmacy system, the prior-authorization system, the patient-engagement systems of multiple institutions, the patient's wearable and self-report data, and (where applicable) the patient's payer data. It has to maintain longitudinal context over months or years. It has to coordinate not just with the patient but with multiple human care-team members across multiple institutions. It has to escalate appropriately when the system has dropped a ball. And it has to do all of this without crossing the boundary into clinical decision-making, which lives with the clinical team, not with the coordinator.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    24[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    25[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few things this recipe is and is not.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    26[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    27[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is the bot that helps a patient navigate a complex multi-step, multi-provider care journey, by maintaining a structured, current view of the patient's referrals, appointments, orders, prior authorizations, test results, care-plan milestones, and care-team contacts; by answering patient questions about the journey grounded in that data; by surfacing pending tasks, blockers, and overdue items; by initiating tasks the patient can complete (scheduling an appointment, completing a pre-visit form, filling out paperwork, refilling a medication, contacting their care navigator); and by escalating to a human care navigator when the bot's tools cannot resolve the situation. The bot operates in coordination with the patient's clinical team and with whatever human care coordination resources the institution has; it extends their reach to the broad middle of patients who have complex journeys but do not qualify for high-touch nurse case management.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    28[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    29[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a clinical decision support tool. The bot does not interpret test results, recommend treatments, recommend medication adjustments, weigh the relative merits of competing care options, or otherwise do the work that lives with the clinical team. The bot's domain is operational coordination, not clinical reasoning. When clinical questions surface in conversation, the bot routes to the appropriate clinical resource (the patient's primary care physician, the relevant specialist, the institution's nurse triage line, the chronic disease coach for chronic-condition questions, the symptom triage bot for new acute symptoms).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    30[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    31[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a scheduling bot. Recipe 11.2 covers appointment scheduling. The care coordination assistant uses the scheduling bot's infrastructure for booking but addresses a broader operational scope: tracking the entire journey, not just the next appointment.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    32[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    33[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a chronic disease coach. Recipe 11.7 covers chronic disease coaching. The care coordination assistant addresses the operational coordination across a complex care journey (procedure preparation, post-discharge transitions, multi-specialty workups, oncology pathways, transplant pathways, and similar). The chronic disease coach addresses ongoing management of established chronic conditions. The two architectures share components and frequently coexist for patients who need both.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    34[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    35[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a substitute for a nurse case manager. The bot extends the case manager's reach; it does not replace the case manager. The patient with a sufficiently complex or high-risk journey still has a nurse case manager (where the institution has the capacity to staff one); the bot handles the routine operational work, freeing the case manager to focus on the cases where their clinical judgment and human relationship-building are most needed. The bot is not the case manager, and the patient is told this explicitly and frequently.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    36[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    37[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a one-system tool. Care coordination journeys cross the EHR, the referral management system, the scheduling system, the imaging system, the lab system, the pharmacy, the prior-authorization system, the institution's patient portal, third-party institution portals, payer systems, and (in many cases) systems the institution does not own. Building a useful care coordination assistant means integrating across all of these, with explicit handling of the systems that do not integrate well and explicit graceful-degradation paths for the integrations that fail.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    38[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    39[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a one-condition tool. The patient with the multi-specialty workup for a structural heart procedure has needs that are different from the patient managing a complex oncology pathway, the patient navigating a kidney-transplant evaluation, the patient transitioning home from a hospital admission, the patient juggling multiple chronic conditions across multiple specialists, and the patient with a complex pediatric care journey. Each pattern has its own care-plan template, its own care-team composition, its own milestone structure, and its own escalation logic. Most institutions deploy the care coordination assistant with a multi-pathway architecture and add pathway-specific protocols over time.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    40[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    41[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a regulatory afterthought. Patient-facing software that helps patients navigate clinical care, particularly when it sends information about care-plan status, prior-authorization status, and clinical-team contacts, sits in the broad neighborhood of patient-engagement software with PHI handling and (in some configurations) on the FDA Software-as-a-Medical-Device line for clinical decision support if the bot crosses into clinical reasoning. <!-- TODO: verify; care-coordination software typically falls outside FDA SaMD when scoped to operational coordination but may approach SaMD if the software produces clinical recommendations; the FDA Clinical Decision Support guidance and ongoing regulatory evolution apply --> The institutional regulatory team is involved from architectural design.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    42[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    43[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a quick win. The deployment timeline is measured in quarters, with the integration work being the dominant pre-launch investment. Each system the bot reads from or writes to is its own integration project, with its own authentication posture, its own data model, its own rate limits, its own failure modes, and its own clinical-leadership and operations stakeholders. Institutions building this expecting a fast time-to-value are usually disappointed. Institutions building this with realistic timelines and the patience for cross-system integration are sometimes able to demonstrate genuinely meaningful patient-experience improvements and operational reductions in dropped-ball failures.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    44[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    45[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The thing to understand before building this is that the care coordination assistant's value is not in any individual conversation. The value is in the accumulated effect of dozens or hundreds of small operational touches across a long care journey, in the dropped balls the bot prevents, in the escalations the bot generates when the system has failed the patient, in the visibility the bot gives the patient into a process that has previously been opaque, and in the scaled extension of care navigation to the broad middle of patients who have complex journeys without qualifying for high-touch case management. A bot evaluated on per-conversation engagement metrics will be optimized for the wrong thing. A bot evaluated on care-journey completion rate, on appointment-no-show rate, on prior-authorization-cycle-time reduction, on dropped-referral rate, on escalation appropriateness, and on patient-experience metrics is being evaluated correctly, and the architectural decisions follow from there.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    46[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    47[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Let's get into it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    48[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    49[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    50[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[K
