[49m[38;5;10m+     51[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Technology: Cross-System Operational Coordination Grounded In Care-Pathway Models, Multi-System Data Integration, and Workflow Automation
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     52[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     53[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why Care Coordination Has Resisted Digital Tools
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     54[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     55[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Care coordination, as a clinical and operational workflow, has been a phone-and-fax-and-spreadsheet problem for several decades, and it remains so for most patients in most institutions in 2026. The reason is structural. Care coordination requires holding, in working memory, a model of the patient's care journey that spans multiple institutions, multiple clinical systems, multiple insurance and benefits systems, multiple referral relationships, multiple test and procedure pathways, and multiple time horizons. The model, when held by a competent nurse care coordinator, includes "what is the destination this patient is trying to reach," "what is the sequence of steps required to get there," "where is the patient in that sequence right now," "what is blocked on what," "what is overdue," "who is responsible for the next step," "what does the patient need from me right now," "what does the patient's care team need from me right now," and "what is the failure mode I should be watching for in this specific patient."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     56[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     57[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Holding this model is most of the cognitive work of care coordination. The patient holds it imperfectly, with whatever supports their family and personal resources allow. The clinical team holds it partially, with each specialty seeing the part of the journey relevant to their domain. The institution holds it inconsistently, with each system holding part of the data and no system holding the integrated patient-centered view. The nurse care coordinator, when the patient has one, holds it relatively completely for the duration of the engagement, and produces (with effort) a coordinated patient experience for the duration. The institution can afford to deploy nurse care coordinators for a small fraction of patients, typically those with the most complex or highest-risk journeys, and the broad middle of patients with complex multi-step journeys navigate them on their own.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     58[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     59[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The first generation of digital tools, roughly the early 2010s through the mid-2010s, tried to address this by giving patients better visibility into their own data through patient portals. The portals were, in most institutions, built per-EHR, with each institution running its own portal, and patients seen at multiple institutions accumulating multiple logins. The portals showed appointments, messages, test results, and a subset of clinical notes, but they did not show the patient's care journey as an integrated sequence, did not surface what was overdue or pending, and did not coordinate across institutions. Patients with complex journeys were shown the data but not given a tool to navigate it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     60[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     61[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The second generation, roughly mid-2010s through early 2020s, was care-management platforms that institutional care managers used internally to track high-risk patients. These platforms gave the care manager a workbench: a patient list, a task queue, an alert feed, and (with effort) a longitudinal view of each patient's interactions with the system. The platforms were largely care-team-facing rather than patient-facing; the patient's view of their journey remained the patient portal, the printed care plan, the legal pad on the kitchen table, and whatever the patient could reconstruct from phone calls. The platforms scaled the care manager's workflow, but they did not extend coordination to patients without a care manager.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     62[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     63[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The third generation, starting roughly 2020 with healthcare's broader digital-front-door investments, added patient-facing care-plan and journey-tracking surfaces in patient apps and portals. These surfaces showed a structured view of the patient's care plan, milestone status, and pending tasks, drawn from the EHR's care-plan resources and the institution's referral and scheduling systems. The clinical evidence for these surfaces is mixed; they helped some patients, but the engagement and adoption patterns largely tracked the same patterns as other digital health tools (the patients who would have done well anyway used them effectively; the patients who needed them most used them least). And the surfaces were structurally constrained to display: they could show the patient where they were in the journey, but they could not have a conversation with the patient about it, could not answer questions about it, could not prompt the patient about overdue items in a useful way, and could not initiate workflow actions on the patient's behalf.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     64[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     65[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The thing that changed the workflow shape, again, is large language models that can carry on a coherent multi-turn conversation grounded in structured care-journey data, can do tool-using operations across multiple back-end systems, can summarize the patient's status in conversational form, can answer the patient's "what should I do next" question with a useful answer, and can recognize when a question or a piece of context is outside the bot's scope and route accordingly. The LLM is not a care coordinator. The LLM is, in the right product design, a tool that lets the care-coordination workflow operate at population scale, with the human care coordinator focused on the cases their judgment and relationship-building are most needed for.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     66[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     67[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The architectural shift is from "display the data" to "have a conversation about the journey, surface the overdue items, initiate the workflow actions, and escalate when the system has failed." The bot's value is concentrated in three places: the cross-system integration that gives the patient a single conversational interface to a fragmented system, the proactive surfacing of pending and overdue items the patient would otherwise have missed, and the operational extension of care coordination to patients who have complex journeys but do not qualify for high-touch case management.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     68[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     69[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### What a Care Coordination Assistant Actually Does
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     70[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     71[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A care coordination assistant is a tool-using LLM with a system prompt that tells it which assistant it is, the patient's authenticated context (active care pathways, current care plan or plans, current care-team contacts, referrals in flight, appointments scheduled and completed, orders pending, prior authorizations in flight, recent test results that the patient's clinical team has released, current medications, current chronic conditions, conversation history, stated patient preferences), access to a structured library of pathway templates (procedure-prep pathways, post-discharge transition pathways, multi-specialty-workup pathways, oncology and transplant pathways, and other institution-specific journeys), and a set of tools for retrieving care-plan and pathway data, retrieving cross-system status (referrals, appointments, orders, prior-authorizations, results), initiating workflow actions (scheduling, form completion, document delivery, message routing), surfacing pending and overdue tasks, and escalating to human care navigators when the situation calls for it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     72[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     73[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The conversation surface is not one conversation. It is a stream of conversational episodes, sometimes initiated by the patient (asking what is next, asking the status of a specific item, reporting a problem), sometimes initiated by the bot per the pathway's milestone calendar (a check-in two days before a scheduled procedure, a post-discharge check-in twenty-four hours after a hospital admission, a pre-appointment confirmation forty-eight hours before a specialist visit), sometimes triggered by a system event (a referral has been pending unscheduled for too long, a prior authorization has been denied, an appointment has been canceled by the practice, a test result has been released that the patient should be aware of), and sometimes triggered by a care-team event (a clinician has requested the patient be reminded of something, a care manager has flagged the patient for outreach).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     74[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     75[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The bot's task surface decomposes roughly as follows.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     76[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     77[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Pathway enrollment and care-plan instantiation.** The patient is enrolled in the care coordination program by their clinical team, by their case manager, by an automated enrollment trigger (a specific procedure scheduled, a specific discharge type, a specific referral pattern), or (in some institutions) by self-enrollment for patients meeting eligibility criteria. The pathway template is selected per the patient's clinical situation and instantiated with patient-specific values: the destination (procedure, evaluation, post-discharge stable state, condition-management baseline), the sequence of milestones, the care-team contacts, the patient-specific timing constraints, and any escalation criteria specific to this patient or pathway. The patient consents to coordination by the bot; the consent specifies which systems the bot can read, which actions the bot can initiate, and which information sharing is permitted.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     78[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     79[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cross-system status retrieval.** When the patient asks "where am I in this journey," the bot retrieves the current state from the relevant systems and synthesizes a conversational answer. Referrals from the EHR's referral module. Appointments from the scheduling system, including pending invitations, scheduled appointments, completed appointments, and canceled appointments. Orders from the EHR (imaging orders, lab orders, consultation orders, procedure orders) with their status (placed, scheduled, completed, canceled, no-shown). Prior authorizations from the institution's PA system or payer systems where the institution has integration. Released test results from the EHR's results module. Care-plan milestones from the care-plan resource. Care-team contacts from the EHR's care-team resource or the institution's directory. The bot synthesizes; the bot does not interpret clinical results.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     80[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     81[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Pending-task surfacing.** When the patient asks "what should I do next," or when the bot initiates a check-in, the bot generates a list of pending tasks specific to the patient's current pathway position. Some tasks are patient-completable (schedule the next appointment, fill out the pre-visit form, complete the patient-questionnaire on the portal, refill the medication, complete the dental clearance). Some tasks are clinician-completable (the cardiologist needs to send the order to the imaging center; the surgeon's office needs to submit the prior authorization). Some tasks are system-completable (the prior authorization is in flight; the referral is awaiting scheduling). The bot distinguishes the categories and surfaces the appropriate next step.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     82[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     83[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Workflow-action initiation.** Where the patient's task is patient-completable and the bot has the integration to do it, the bot initiates the workflow action: opens a scheduling flow that hands off to recipe 11.2 with pathway context attached; opens a refill flow that hands off to recipe 11.3; surfaces a pre-visit intake form that hands off to recipe 11.4; routes a benefits or prior-authorization question to the benefits navigator (recipe 11.5); generates a message to the relevant clinician with appropriate routing. The bot's job is to reduce the patient's friction, not to handle every task itself; the bot orchestrates rather than performs the underlying transactions.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     84[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     85[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Pathway-milestone proactive engagement.** The bot runs scheduled engagement per the pathway's milestone calendar. Pre-procedure prep reminders at the appropriate intervals (two weeks, one week, three days, one day, six hours, depending on the procedure). Post-discharge check-ins (twenty-four hours, seventy-two hours, seven days, fourteen days, thirty days for typical discharge pathways). Pre-appointment reminders calibrated to the specialty (forty-eight hours for routine, longer for high-prep procedures, with intake-form reminders nested in). Lab-result-acknowledgment prompts (when a result has been released, the bot follows up to confirm the patient saw it and understood the next step).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     86[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     87[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cross-pathway reconciliation.** Patients in complex care journeys frequently have multiple active pathways: a procedure prep pathway plus a chronic-disease management pathway plus a routine preventive-care pathway. The bot reconciles across pathways, surfaces overlaps and dependencies (the diabetes management goal of HbA1c under 7 may be a prerequisite for the procedure approval; the post-discharge medication reconciliation interacts with the chronic-disease medication regimen), and flags conflicts to the care team where the bot detects them.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     88[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     89[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Escalation routing.** When the bot detects a dropped ball (a referral has been awaiting scheduling for two weeks past the pathway's expected interval, a prior authorization has been denied without follow-up, an appointment was canceled and not rescheduled, a result has been released with explicit clinician-followup requirements that have not been completed), the bot escalates to the patient's care navigator (where one is assigned) or the institution's care-coordination triage queue (where care navigators are pooled). The escalation includes the patient context, the pathway context, the specific blocker, and the bot's recommended action.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     90[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     91[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Sensitive-disclosure handling.** Care-coordination conversations sometimes surface things outside operational coordination: a patient discloses that they cannot afford the procedure copay, that they have transportation barriers, that they are caring for a family member and cannot keep the appointment schedule, that they are having a problem with one of their clinicians, that they are reconsidering whether to proceed with the procedure, that they are having a mental-health crisis. Each requires routing: financial-assistance pathway, transportation-assistance pathway, social-work pathway, patient-relations pathway, the chronic disease coach or the primary clinical team, the mental-health support pathway (recipe 11.8) or direct emergency routing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     92[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     93[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-team reporting.** The patient's care navigator (where one is assigned) and the patient's primary clinical team have visibility into the bot's coordination activities through structured reports: real-time alerts for blockers and concerning developments, weekly digests for active-pathway patients, milestone-completion reports, and ad-hoc summaries.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     94[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     95[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Off-boarding when the journey completes.** Pathways have endings. The procedure happens; the post-discharge transition stabilizes; the multi-specialty workup completes. The bot supports a respectful transition with structured journey-summary delivery to the care team and the patient, and a clear path back if the patient enters a new pathway.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     96[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     97[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why a Generic LLM Cannot Run a Care Coordination Assistant
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     98[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     99[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A naive product approach would be: take a generalist LLM, give it a chat surface, paste in some referral and appointment data, and have it coordinate. This breaks in several specific ways, each with patient-experience and operational consequences.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    100[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    101[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no consistent view of the patient's journey across systems.** Care coordination requires reading across the EHR's referral module, the scheduling system, the imaging system, the lab system, the pharmacy, the prior-authorization system, the patient portal, third-party portals, and (sometimes) payer systems. Without a structured cross-system data integration, the LLM operates with whatever the patient pastes in, which is partial, sometimes incorrect, and not stable across conversations. The cross-system integration is the architectural primitive that distinguishes the coordinator from a patient-portal-text-summarizer.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    102[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    103[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of which actions are patient-completable, clinician-completable, or system-completable.** Without explicit task-classification logic, the LLM tells the patient to do things only the clinician can do, fails to tell the patient about things they could do, and conflates "the system is working on it" with "the patient needs to do something." The task-classification logic is part of the architecture, encoded in the pathway templates and the tool-call interpretation, not left to the LLM.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    104[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    105[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of pathway expected-timing or dropped-ball detection.** Care coordination depends on knowing the expected timeline for each step, comparing actual progress to expected, and flagging deviations. Without structured pathway-timing data, the LLM cannot tell the difference between "the referral is on track" and "the referral has been dropped." The pathway templates encode expected timing; the structured comparison logic detects deviation; the LLM does not estimate timing from scratch.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    106[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    107[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has clinical-content drift when the patient asks clinical questions.** A patient in a coordination conversation will inevitably ask clinical questions: what does this test result mean, why is the surgeon recommending this procedure over that one, what should I expect from this medication. The LLM, prompted to be helpful, will drift into clinical reasoning that is outside the bot's scope. The scope discipline (reinforced by prompts, output-safety filters, and routing logic) keeps the bot in the operational lane and routes clinical questions to the appropriate clinical resource.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    108[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    109[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of multi-institution data semantics.** A "consultation" at one institution is a "specialist visit" at another and a "referral encounter" at a third. A "referral" can mean an order, a scheduled appointment, or a completed encounter, depending on the system. Without explicit data-model normalization, the LLM produces inconsistent answers as the patient moves across institutions. The normalization is part of the architecture; the integration layer translates each source's vocabulary into the bot's internal model.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    110[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    111[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of action authorization.** Some actions the bot can initiate on the patient's behalf require specific consent, specific verification, or specific routing through human approval. Sending a message to the patient's clinician is one set of permissions; submitting a prior-authorization on the patient's behalf is another; canceling an appointment is yet another. The action authorization model is encoded explicitly, not inferred by the LLM.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    112[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    113[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of escalation criteria.** Without explicit dropped-ball detection thresholds and escalation-routing rules, the LLM either escalates everything (alert fatigue for human care navigators) or escalates nothing (the patient's blocker remains). The thresholds are pathway-specific, signed off by the clinical and operations leadership, and are operationalized in the pathway templates.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    114[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    115[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has compliance implications for cross-institution data.** Care-coordination conversations may surface PHI from institutions other than the one running the bot. The privacy and consent posture for cross-institution data sharing has specific HIPAA TPO (treatment, payment, healthcare operations) considerations and, in some cases, state-specific privacy considerations exceeding the HIPAA baseline. <!-- TODO: verify; cross-institution PHI sharing under HIPAA TPO is permitted under specific conditions including treatment relationships and BAAs; specific compliance considerations vary by state and configuration --> The legal team is involved in the consent and data-sharing posture.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    116[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    117[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of staying within scope when patients ask for clinical advice.** Same as in the previous bots. The coordinator's scope is operational; clinical questions route to clinical resources.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    118[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    119[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of the human care navigator's workflow.** The bot is a coordination layer that extends the human care navigator's reach. The handoff to the navigator has to fit the navigator's workflow: the right context, the right priority, the right communication channel, the right expectation about response time. Building the bot without the navigator's workflow in mind produces a bot the navigators do not trust and do not use, which is an expensive failure mode.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    120[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    121[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### What the Coordinator Has To Do That the Previous Bots Did Not
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    122[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    123[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Recipes 11.1 through 11.8 established the patterns this recipe inherits: input safety screening with continuous emergency screening, identity verification, tool-use orchestration, output safety screening, audit logging, per-cohort monitoring, scope discipline, prompt-injection defense, graceful degradation, longitudinal-context loading, citation grounding, behavior-change-stage tracking, crisis screening (where applicable), warm handoff. The care coordination assistant adds eight structural commitments those recipes did not have at this depth.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    124[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    125[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Multi-system data integration as architectural primitive.** The bot reads from the EHR's referral, scheduling, orders, results, care-plan, and care-team modules; from the imaging and lab systems; from the pharmacy; from the prior-authorization system; from the patient portal; from third-party institution portals where the institution has data-sharing arrangements; and from payer systems where supported. The integration layer is the bot's primary architectural component, and it dwarfs the LLM-orchestration component in complexity.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    126[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    127[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Pathway-as-code with clinical-and-operations leadership ownership.** Each care pathway has a structured template, owned jointly by the relevant clinical-specialty leadership (cardiology for the structural-heart pathway, oncology for cancer pathways, transplant medicine for transplant pathways, hospital medicine and discharge planning for post-discharge transitions, primary care for routine-coordination pathways) and care-coordination operations leadership (which owns the operational milestones, the expected timing, the escalation criteria, and the human-navigator workflow integration). The pathway templates are signed off, version-controlled, and reviewed annually.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    128[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    129[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cross-pathway reconciliation logic.** Patients in multiple pathways have dependencies and conflicts the bot must reconcile. The reconciliation logic is encoded in the architecture; the LLM surfaces the reconciliation, but the rules are deterministic and reviewed by clinical leadership.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    130[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    131[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Workflow-action authorization and audit.** Each workflow action the bot can initiate on the patient's behalf has a defined authorization model, an audit record, and (where applicable) a human-approval step. The action surface is restricted; the bot does not attempt actions outside the surface.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    132[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    133[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Dropped-ball detection with pathway-specific timing.** Each pathway specifies expected timing for each step. The dropped-ball detection logic compares actual progress to expected and flags deviations. The thresholds are signed off by clinical and operations leadership.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    134[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    135[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cross-institution data sharing posture with explicit consent.** The patient's consent specifies which institutions' data the bot can read, which actions across institutions the bot can initiate, and which information the bot can share back across institutions. The consent posture is reviewed by legal counsel and is operationalized in the data-access layer.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    136[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    137[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-team and care-navigator integration as first-class capability.** The human care navigator's workflow integration is part of production scope, not phase 2. Real-time alerts, daily and weekly digests, navigator-facing patient-context summaries, and the navigator-side handoff and feedback tooling are designed and built with care-coordination operations leadership.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    138[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    139[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Operational-outcome correlation as core post-launch commitment.** The coordinator's value shows up in operational metrics: care-journey completion rate, appointment no-show rate, prior-authorization cycle time, dropped-referral rate, escalation appropriateness, time-to-resolution for blockers, patient-experience metrics. The outcome-correlation pipeline is multi-quarter post-launch work and is operationally significant.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    140[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    141[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The rest is largely the same as the previous chapter 11 recipes.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    142[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    143[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### The Coordination Reality
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    144[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    145[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few notes on what makes care coordination specifically harder than the other patient-facing bot use cases.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    146[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    147[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The integration work dominates.** In the chronic disease coach (recipe 11.7), the relationship-quality engineering dominates. In the mental-health support bot (recipe 11.8), the crisis screening and the disclosure handling dominate. In the care coordination assistant, the cross-system integration dominates. Each system the bot reads from or writes to is its own integration project, with its own authentication posture, its own data model, its own rate limits, its own failure modes, and its own ownership stakeholders. Most institutions discover, partway through the project, that their cross-system integration baseline is meaningfully worse than they assumed: data that was supposed to be in the EHR is actually in a separate system, scheduling data that was supposed to be queryable through one API is split across multiple APIs, prior-authorization status that was supposed to be visible is actually only visible through the payer's portal that requires a different login. The integration work consumes most of the project budget and most of the project timeline.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    148[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    149[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The semantic normalization is not a one-time project.** Each source system encodes care-journey concepts differently. A "referral" in one system is a different entity than a "referral" in another. An "appointment" can be at the encounter level, the visit level, the slot level, or the procedure level depending on the system. A "completed" status can mean different things in different sources. The semantic normalization is an ongoing investment, not a one-time mapping; new source systems enter, existing source systems update their data models, and the institution's clinical workflows change.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    150[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    151[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The data freshness and reliability posture is heterogeneous.** Some source systems update in real time; others update overnight; others update only when a human enters data; some have known data-quality issues that mean the bot has to be cautious about stating things as definitive. The architecture surfaces freshness explicitly and degrades gracefully when sources are stale or unreachable.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    152[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    153[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The patient's view and the clinical team's view diverge in specific ways.** The clinical team sees orders, encounters, results, and care-plan elements that may not be released to the patient. The patient sees portal-released subsets, with timing controlled by institutional policies and by the clinician's release decisions. The bot operates from the patient's view (the bot is patient-facing), with explicit awareness that the patient's view may not include things the clinician knows. The bot does not surface clinical content that the clinician has not released; the bot does not pretend to know things the patient cannot see.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    154[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    155[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The cross-institution data picture is uneven.** In ideal cases, the institutions share data through HIE participation, TEFCA participation, and direct integration. In typical cases, the patient is a member of multiple institutional systems with no integration; the patient's view of their cross-institution journey lives only in the patient's own head and the patient's own paper records. The architecture handles both cases: ideal-case integration for institutions where it works; patient-self-report fallback for institutions where it does not. <!-- TODO: verify; HIE and TEFCA participation in 2026 has expanded substantially since the 2020 baseline but remains uneven across institutions; specific connectivity varies by region and institution -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    156[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    157[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-team-contact freshness is a specific operational concern.** The patient's care team is a list of contacts that changes over time. The cardiologist's office has a new scheduler. The surgeon's office has a new coordinator. The patient's primary care physician left the practice and the patient is reassigned. The institutional directory may or may not be current. The architecture has explicit care-team-contact freshness handling and patient-self-report fallback.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    158[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    159[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Escalation calibration is a multi-axis problem.** The dropped-ball detection thresholds need to be tight enough that real blockers are surfaced and loose enough that human care navigators are not buried in alerts. The calibration is per-pathway, per-step, per-cohort, and per-institution. Mis-calibration produces alert fatigue or missed escalations, both of which damage the operational posture.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    160[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    161[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Human care-navigator-trust is the dominant adoption barrier.** The bot's value is realized through care navigators acting on the bot's escalations, integrating with the bot's pathway-tracking, and trusting the bot's view of patient status. Care navigators who do not trust the bot will do their work in parallel, ignore the bot's alerts, and produce a deployment where the bot is technically operational and operationally useless. Building care-navigator trust is multi-quarter relationship-building work.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    162[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    163[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Clinical-team adoption is the secondary adoption barrier.** Clinicians who do not trust the bot to handle their patients' coordination questions will continue to handle them themselves, which preserves the clinician's caseload bottleneck and limits the bot's value. Building clinician trust is multi-quarter work, requiring transparent escalation behavior, careful scope discipline, and visibility into the bot's interactions with the clinician's patients.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    164[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    165[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Patient-experience design is harder than it looks.** Patients in complex care journeys are often anxious, sometimes ill, sometimes in pain, sometimes overwhelmed, sometimes elderly, sometimes managing the journey on behalf of a family member. The bot's tone and pacing must be calibrated for this audience. A bot that feels like a portal interface is a bot that does not help; a bot that feels like a competent and slightly warm coordinator is a bot the patient comes back to.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    166[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    167[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Multi-language and multi-literacy support is essential, not optional.** The patient population requiring complex-care-coordination assistance is heterogeneous; the language and literacy levels at which the bot operates must accommodate the population the institution serves.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    168[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    169[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Equity considerations are amplified.** Patients who navigate complex journeys most easily are typically the patients with the most resources, support, and health literacy. The patients who need the bot most are typically the patients with the fewest. A bot that primarily helps the patients who would have managed without it is a bot that exacerbates rather than reduces health disparities. Per-cohort engagement and outcome monitoring is a launch-gate.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    170[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    171[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Operational ownership crosses many teams.** The bot sits at the intersection of clinical-specialty leadership (per pathway), care-coordination operations, the IT teams owning each integrated source system, compliance, regulatory, the call center, patient experience, and (in some institutions) the payer-side operations team. The cross-team operational coordination of building the bot is non-trivial and is, itself, a coordination problem.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    172[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    173[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Build-vs-buy is mature for some segments and not for others.** Several mature commercial vendors offer care-coordination platforms with patient-facing surfaces, EHR integration, and (in some cases) AI-assisted features. Most major institutions deploy hybrid architectures: vendor-provided care-management platform for the care-team-facing workflow, in-house or vendor-partner orchestration for the patient-facing conversational coordinator, with the institution's own integration into the heterogeneous source systems.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    174[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    175[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Where the Field Has Moved
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    176[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    177[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few practical updates worth knowing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    178[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    179[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **TEFCA participation has expanded substantially.** The Trusted Exchange Framework and Common Agreement, established by ONC, has expanded since the 2022 launch with multiple Qualified Health Information Networks (QHINs) operational and broad institutional participation. <!-- TODO: verify; TEFCA participation in 2026 has expanded substantially since the 2022 launch with multiple QHINs operational; specific participation varies by institution and region --> Cross-institution data exchange for treatment is more available than in prior years; the architecture should anticipate continued expansion.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    180[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    181[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **FHIR R4 adoption is broad.** Most major EHR vendors and many healthcare information systems support FHIR R4 endpoints for read access to patient-level data, with US Core implementation guides providing standardized resource profiles. <!-- TODO: verify; FHIR R4 adoption is broad in 2026 with most major EHRs supporting it; US Core implementation guide adoption is widespread; specific endpoint availability varies by institution --> The integration layer should target FHIR R4 first and degrade to vendor-specific APIs only where FHIR is unavailable.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    182[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    183[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Information Blocking rules continue to influence data-sharing posture.** The 21st Century Cures Act information-blocking rules require institutions to share patient data when requested unless a specific exception applies, with regulatory penalties for non-compliance. <!-- TODO: verify; the information-blocking rules under the 21st Century Cures Act have continued to be enforced with specific guidance and rulemaking from ONC and OIG; specific compliance varies --> Care-coordination architectures should anticipate that more data is shareable than in prior years, while still respecting the legitimate exceptions.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    184[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    185[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Tool-using LLMs handle multi-system orchestration well when grounded carefully.** The function-calling pattern from the previous chapter 11 recipes maps to care coordination. The LLM produces tool calls that retrieve cross-system status, surface pending tasks, initiate workflow actions, and post events for downstream operations.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    186[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    187[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Patient-facing care-pathway surfaces are increasingly common in EHR vendor products.** Major EHR vendors have invested in patient-facing journey-tracking features in their patient-portal products. <!-- TODO: verify; major EHR vendors including Epic, Oracle Health (formerly Cerner), Athena, eClinicalWorks, and others have invested in patient-portal journey-tracking features in 2024-2026 --> The architectural decision is whether to build the conversational coordinator on top of the vendor's care-pathway data model, alongside it, or as a replacement; most institutions choose "on top of" for reasons of vendor-leverage and migration risk.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    188[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    189[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Outcome demonstration is mixed but trending positive for care-coordination AI deployments.** Studies of digital care-coordination programs have shown improvements in appointment-completion rates, prior-authorization cycle times, dropped-referral rates, and patient-experience measures, with the magnitude of effect varying by program design, pathway focus, and patient population. <!-- TODO: verify; the evidence base for digital care-coordination programs includes published studies of programs across multiple institutions; specific outcome figures vary by study and program --> The ROI demonstration is stronger when the analysis includes downstream-event reduction (avoided no-shows, avoided redundant testing, avoided readmissions tied to coordination failures) than when the analysis focuses only on direct engagement metrics.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    190[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    191[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Equity and disparity monitoring is an active area of attention.** Per-cohort monitoring of engagement, escalation rates, journey-completion rates, and patient-experience metrics is essential and is non-trivial.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    192[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    193[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Build-vs-buy is mature for the care-management workbench layer; less mature for the conversational coordinator.** Several mature commercial vendors offer care-management platforms; the patient-facing conversational layer is less standardized, with most institutions building it (or partnering with a small set of vendors who specialize in it) rather than relying on a generic vendor offering.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    194[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    195[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    196[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
